Objective: To develop and validate a brain-computer interface (BCI)-compatible sleep staging algorithm specifically optimized for menopausal women, addressing the unique challenges of EEG analysis in this population.

Methods: Using polysomnographic data from 72 subjects across three independent databases (Sleep-EDF: 28 subjects, ISRUC-Sleep: 20 subjects, DREAMS: 24 subjects), we developed MenoSCA-FBTS (Menopause-Specific Covariance-based Adaptive Filtering with Adaptive Temporal Smoothing), a lightweight BCI-ready algorithm integrating Riemannian geometry, multi-band EEG features, and menopause-specific adaptations. Comprehensive benchmarking against 6 state-of-the-art algorithms was conducted.

Results: MenoSCA-FBTS achieved 87.8\% accuracy across all datasets, outperforming YASA (87.0\%), Random Forest (86.7\%), TinySleepNet (85.4\%), EEGNet (78.5\%), and MiniRocket (72.0\%). Critically, the algorithm demonstrated low computational complexity (training time: 125s; inference: <10ms/epoch), making it suitable for real-time BCI deployment. Menopausal women showed consistent sleep architecture alterations: reduced N3 deep sleep (6.8\% vs. 16.7\% in young women) and increased sleep fragmentation (2.5-fold higher wake-to-N1 transitions).

Conclusion: MenoSCA-FBTS represents a BCI-optimized solution for accurate, low-latency sleep staging in menopausal women. Its lightweight design enables integration into wearable BCI devices for long-term sleep monitoring, addressing a critical gap in menopause sleep research and clinical care.
